## ⚠️ Limitation: Pi Extensions Are Active on Load

**Pi doesn't have a built-in way to make all extensions passive by default.** When an extension loads, it runs its setup code immediately.

For example:
- `workflow-orchestrator.ts` prints "Workflow orchestrator active" immediately
- Extensions that register event handlers do so right away
- There's no "passive mode" flag in pi's extension system

---

## Workarounds (Closest to What You Want)

### Option 1: Use `pi-mi` for Truly Minimal Mode
```bash
pi-mi  # No extensions at all - truly passive
```

### Option 2: Modify Your Custom Extensions to Be Passive
For extensions in `~/.config/pi/extensions/`, you can modify them to check for activation:

**Example - make workflow-orchestrator passive:**
```typescript
export default function (pi: ExtensionAPI) {
  let activated = false;

  // Only activate when user types /workflow-orchestrator
  pi.registerCommand("workflow-orchestrator", {
    description: "Activate workflow orchestrator",
    handler: async (_args, ctx) => {
      activated = true;
      ctx.ui.notify("Workflow orchestrator activated!", "info");
      // Now register the actual behavior
      // ... rest of extension code
    }
  });

  // Don't do anything until activated
  if (!activated) return;

  // Original extension code here...
}
```

### Option 3: Use Plan-Mode as a Template
The `plan-mode` extension already does this - it has an `enabled` flag that defaults to `false`.

